## 3. Edit `CLAUDE.md` for this project _MANUAL_

The agents read these fields:

- [ ] `## Overview` — short description of what the project does
- [ ] `## Tech Stack` — languages, libraries, versions
- [ ] `## Skills Path` — path to superpowers skills (must match `SUPERPOWERS_SKILLS_DIR` in `project.env`)
- [ ] `## Architecture` — directory layout
- [ ] `## Entry Points` — test / lint / format / run commands
- [ ] `## QA Standards` — domain-specific rules (this section is **mandatory**; the tester agent fails the task if it's missing or empty). `init-project.sh` injected the template you chose; customise it.
- [ ] `### Task Tracker` — `tracker:` field (`file`, `github-issues`, or `azure-boards`). `.claude/env.sh` reads this line and exports `TRACKER_BACKEND` automatically; you do not set it by hand. **Note:** `azure-boards` has all 12 verbs implemented in `lib/tracker/tracker_azure.sh`, but the surrounding bootstrap (init-azure-tracker script, `AZ_*` variables in `project.env.template`, on-call agent Azure branch, AZURE-TRACKER-GUIDE) is not yet shipped — only `file` and `github-issues` are bootstrappable end-to-end via `init-project.sh`.
- [ ] `### GitHub Project` — fill in `github_project_action`, `github_project_number`, `project:`, `repo:` if using GitHub Issues mode
- [ ] `### Agent Variant` — `github` or `file`

---

## 4. Edit `.claude/project.env` _MANUAL + scriptable_

This is the file that tells every agent which GitHub project board to talk
to and where to find the superpowers skills. `init-project.sh` populated
`GH_OWNER` automatically; the rest is yours.

### 4a. Repo identity (manual)

Open `.claude/project.env` and set:

```bash
export GH_REPO="<your-repo>"
export GH_PROJECT_NUMBER=<your-project-number>          # see step 4b
export GH_PROJECT_ID="<PVT_kw...>"    # see step 4b
```

(`GH_OWNER` should already be filled in. Adjust if you're targeting a
different account or org.)

### 4b. Find the project number and project ID (scriptable)

If you already know the project number (visible in the URL: `github.com/users/<your-github-user>/projects/<your-project-number>`):

```bash
gh project view <your-project-number> --owner <your-github-user> --format json | jq '{number: .number, id: .id, title: .title}'
```

Copy `number` → `GH_PROJECT_NUMBER`, `id` → `GH_PROJECT_ID`.

### 4c. Find field IDs (scriptable)

```bash
gh project field-list <your-project-number> --owner <your-github-user> --format json | jq '.fields[] | {name, id, type}'
```

Map the output to the env vars by matching on `name`:

| Field name in your board | Variable in `project.env`  |
|---|---|
| `Pipeline` (single-select) | `GH_FIELD_PIPELINE`  |
| `Agent` (single-select)    | `GH_FIELD_AGENT`     |
| `Status` (single-select)   | `GH_FIELD_STATUS`    |
| `QA Cycle` (number)        | `GH_FIELD_QA_CYCLE`  |

If your board uses different field names, either rename them on the board or
rename the variables consistently across all agent files.

### 4d. Find option IDs (scriptable)

```bash
gh project field-list <your-project-number> --owner <your-github-user> --format json \
  | jq '.fields[] | select(.name=="Pipeline") | .options[] | {name, id}'
```

Repeat for `Agent` and `Status`. Map each option's `id` to its variable:

**Pipeline options** (`GH_FIELD_PIPELINE`):

| Option name | Variable                       |
|---|---|
| Backlog     | `GH_PIPELINE_BACKLOG`          |
| Development | `GH_PIPELINE_DEVELOPMENT`      |
| QA          | `GH_PIPELINE_QA`               |
| Acceptance  | `GH_PIPELINE_ACCEPTANCE`       |
| Documentation | `GH_PIPELINE_DOCUMENTATION`  |
| Done        | `GH_PIPELINE_DONE`             |
| Blocked     | `GH_PIPELINE_BLOCKED`          |

**Agent options** (`GH_FIELD_AGENT`):

| Option name | Variable             |
|---|---|
| SWE         | `GH_AGENT_SWE`       |
| QA          | `GH_AGENT_QA`        |
| PM          | `GH_AGENT_PM`        |
| TechWriter  | `GH_AGENT_TECHWRITER`|
| Human       | `GH_AGENT_HUMAN`     |

**Status options** (`GH_FIELD_STATUS`):

| Option name      | Variable             |
|---|---|
| Backlog          | `GH_STATUS_BACKLOG`  |
| In documentation | `GH_STATUS_IN_DOCS`  |
| Done             | `GH_STATUS_DONE`     |

If any option is missing on your board, **create it on the board first** — do
not invent placeholders in `project.env`. The agents will fail loudly if an
ID is unset.

### 4e. Install superpowers and verify the skills path

The dev-team uses [obra/superpowers](https://github.com/obra/superpowers) for
process discipline (TDD, brainstorming, debugging, …).

**Install once per host** — pick whichever fits your tool:

```bash
# Claude Code (preferred):
/plugin install superpowers@claude-plugins-official

# Other tools (Copilot CLI, etc.):
git clone https://github.com/obra/superpowers ~/superpowers
```

`env.sh` auto-detects the install — you usually do **not** need to set
`SUPERPOWERS_SKILLS_DIR` by hand. It checks, in order:

1. `SUPERPOWERS_SKILLS_DIR` if you set it in `project.env` (overrides everything)
2. `~/.claude/plugins/cache/claude-plugins-official/superpowers/*/skills` (Claude Code plugin path; latest version wins)
3. `~/superpowers/skills`, `~/github/superpowers/skills`, `~/code/superpowers/skills`, `../../github/superpowers/skills`

Verify the resolution succeeded:

```bash
source .claude/env.sh
ls "${SUPERPOWERS_SKILLS_DIR}/test-driven-development/SKILL.md"
```

If neither auto-detect nor an explicit override resolves, `env.sh` prints a
warning pointing at this section. Set `SUPERPOWERS_SKILLS_DIR` manually in
`project.env` to an absolute path to override:

```bash
export SUPERPOWERS_SKILLS_DIR="/absolute/path/to/superpowers/skills"
```

### 4f. Required GitHub Issue labels _MANUAL_

The agents transition issues with these labels. If `init-project.sh` was
run with `--github`, it already invoked `init-github-tracker.sh` to create
them. Verify with:

```bash
gh label list --repo "${GH_OWNER}/${GH_REPO}" | grep -E "needs-grooming|role-pm|qa-cycle-1"
```

If labels are missing:

```bash
bash .claude/../scripts/init-github-tracker.sh "${GH_OWNER}/${GH_REPO}"
```

