## 4-AZ. Edit `.claude/project.env` for Azure DevOps mode _MANUAL + scriptable_

Skip this section if you are not using `tracker: azure-boards`.

### 4-AZ a. Org / project / repo identity (manual)

Open `.claude/project.env` and set:

```bash
export AZ_ORG="<your-azure-org>"          # slug ("myorg") or full URL ("https://dev.azure.com/myorg")
export AZ_PROJECT="<your-azure-project>"  # case-sensitive project name
export AZ_REPO="<your-azure-repo>"        # case-sensitive Azure Repos repository name
```

Optional fields, leave blank for defaults:

```bash
export AZ_AREA_PATH=""           # default: AZ_PROJECT (the project root)
export AZ_ITERATION_PATH=""      # blank → backlog (no sprint)
export AZ_WORK_ITEM_TYPE=""      # default: "Task" — set to "User Story", "Bug", etc. as needed
```

### 4-AZ b. Verify the connection (scriptable)

```bash
az account show >/dev/null && echo "az: logged in"
az devops project show --org "https://dev.azure.com/${AZ_ORG#https://dev.azure.com/}" --project "${AZ_PROJECT}" --query name
az repos show --org "https://dev.azure.com/${AZ_ORG#https://dev.azure.com/}" --project "${AZ_PROJECT}" --repository "${AZ_REPO}" --query name
```

All three commands should print without error. If `az devops` is not a known
command, run `az extension add --name azure-devops` first.

### 4-AZ c. Process template assumption

`tracker_azure.sh` maps the pipeline to ADO `System.State` values from the
**Agile** process template (`New` / `Active` / `Resolved` / `Closed`). If
your project uses Scrum, CMMI, or Basic, set the four `AZ_STATE_*` env
vars in `.claude/project.env` instead of editing the source — this keeps
the override per-project and survives re-bootstraps:

```bash
# Scrum:
export AZ_STATE_NEW="New"
export AZ_STATE_ACTIVE="Committed"
export AZ_STATE_RESOLVED="Done"
export AZ_STATE_CLOSED="Done"

# CMMI:
export AZ_STATE_NEW="Proposed"
export AZ_STATE_ACTIVE="Active"
export AZ_STATE_RESOLVED="Resolved"
export AZ_STATE_CLOSED="Closed"

# Basic:
export AZ_STATE_NEW="To Do"
export AZ_STATE_ACTIVE="Doing"
export AZ_STATE_RESOLVED="Doing"
export AZ_STATE_CLOSED="Done"
```

Confirm your project's actual state names with:

```bash
az boards work-item show --id <existing-id> -o json | jq '.fields["System.State"]'
```

The state-vocabulary tags themselves (`needs-grooming`, `ready-for-dev`, …)
are process-independent and never need to be overridden.

### 4-AZ d. Authentication for headless / CI runs

Interactive workstations: `az login` once and you are done.

Non-interactive (CI, agents running unattended): export `AZURE_DEVOPS_EXT_PAT`
to a Personal Access Token with at least:

- **Work Items**: Read & Write (create / update / comment)
- **Code**: Read (so `az repos show` succeeds)

The PAT is read by the `azure-devops` extension automatically; you do not
pass it as a flag.

### 4-AZ e. Initial sanity check

If `init-project.sh` was run with `--azure`, it already invoked
`init-azure-tracker.sh`. To re-run:

```bash
bash .claude/../scripts/init-azure-tracker.sh
```

This verifies the connection, prints the tag vocabulary the agents use,
and warns if the project's process template is not one of those mapped by
the backend.

